  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key examples include:\n\n1. United States:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. European Union:\n- Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n\n3. International standards:\n- FATF global guidelines\n- Basel Committee recommendations\n\nThese regulations typically require financial institutions to:\n- Perform customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n- Screen customers against watch lists\n\nFinancial institutions like banks, credit unions, investment firms, and money transfer services must comply with these regulations and can face significant penalties for non-compliance.",
